A disaster is almost never a single, isolated incident.
It is a cascade of interconnected events in which one hazard triggers additional hazards, system failures, or operational degradations.

The “main disaster” is only the initial node — not the full scope of severity or impact.

Disaster chaining exists to capture these cascading relationships so that response systems can:

fetch the correct situational data in real time,

identify secondary and tertiary hazards before they occur,

anticipate operational impacts across infrastructure, health, and logistics,

and support faster, more accurate emergency deployment.

By modeling disasters as causal chains rather than isolated events, the system provides a more complete and actionable picture of emerging conditions.

This is the structural graph, not the narrative.
Below are the current disaster chains.
(Not all possible chains are represented at the time of this document’s publication.)

